[{"name": "Zermelo's theorem (game theory)", "description": "In game theory, Zermelo's theorem is a theorem about finite two-person games of perfect information in which the players move alternately and in which chance does not affect the decision making process. It says that if the game cannot end in a draw, then one of the two players must have a winning strategy (i.e. can force a win). An alternate statement is that for a game meeting all of these conditions except the condition that a draw is now possible, then either the first-player can force a win, or the second-player can force a win, or both players can at least force a draw.[1]\nThe theorem is named after Ernst Zermelo, a German mathematician and logician, who proved the theorem for the example game of chess in 1913.", "source_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%27s_theorem_(game_theory)", "metadata": {"categories": ["Game theory", "History of mathematics", "Mathematical theorems"], "related_articles": ["well-ordering theorem", "game theory", "perfect information", "Ernst Zermelo", "chess", "chess", "White", "Black", "computer science", "model checking", "value interaction", "zero-sum", "International Congress of Mathematicians", "set theory", "proof by contradiction", "pigeonhole principle", "D\u00e9nes K\u0151nig", "fifty move rule", "threefold repetition", "Nash equilibrium", "L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Kalm\u00e1r", "IEEE Intelligent Systems", "doi", "S2CID", "Ebbinghaus, Heinz-Dieter", "ISBN", "9783642080500", "doi", "doi", "v", "t", "e", "Game theory", "Glossary", "Game theorists", "Games", "Traditional Game Theory", "Definitions", "Asynchrony", "Bayesian regret", "Best response", "Bounded rationality", "Cheap talk", "Coalition", "Complete contract", "Complete information", "Complete mixing", "Confrontation analysis", "Conjectural variation", "Contingent cooperator", "Coopetition", "Cooperative game theory", "Dynamic inconsistency", "Escalation of commitment", "Farsightedness", "Game semantics", "Hier